[{"message":"# Flappy Bird Part 1\n\n## Overview of the Game\n> Flappy Bird is the most popular game on the Internet these days. It is a simple one-button game in which you have to navigate our beloved bird past the obstacles.\n> You do this by clicking your mouse repeatedly. Each time you click, the bird flies up. Don't make it fly too high or it will die. This means you have to tap at the right moments to make the bird go as far as you can!\n\n## Overview of the Tutorial\nThis tutorial consists two parts. In the first part, we will create the game area with moving poles.\n\nBy the end of the tutorial, you will learn:\n- place elements and game layouts in HTML5 games\n- style elements in HTMl5 games\n- control element's layout and style dynamically through JavaScript\n- create animations in HTML5 games\n\n## Step 1. Starter Code\nLet's first create an HTML5 starter template with an H1 element containing the title of the game.\n","hash":"4bb5a4c"},{"message":"## Step 2. Create Basic Layout of the Game\nIn this step, we divided the page into three parts --- the game title and instructions area; the game area; and the game info area which contains a restart button.\nWe use basic CSS styling to make the elements centered in the middle. We also add a background color to the game area.","hash":"6bb2298"},{"message":"## Step 3. Position the Bird and Poles\nNext, we create a div as bird and two poles inside the game-area div. We use the CSS attribute `background` to set the background of the bird div to be an image. We then use the CSS attribute `background-size:contain` to make the background image scale as large as possible within its container without cropping or stretching the image. If the container is larger than the image, this will result in image tiling. Thus we use the CSS attribute `background-repeat:no-repeat` to prevent image tiling.\n\nIn this step, we also work on the positioning of the game area.\n\nA page element with **relative positioning** gives you the control to **absolutely position** children elements inside of it.\nIf you are interested to learn more, you can read [this article](https://css-tricks.com/absolute-positioning-inside-relative-positioning/)\n\nWe use `position:absolute` on the bird and poles, so that they are positioned relative to the positioned ancestor --- which is currently the body. We then set the game-area to `position:relative` so that the position of the birds are relative to the game-area. We then use `top`, `left` to define the position of the bird and the poles.","hash":"9a51e4b"},{"message":"## Step 4. Implement the Button Clicking Behavior\nNext, let's insert `index.js` which controls the behavior of the game. We will add an event listener to the restart button. We are not doing anything inside the `startGame` function right now.","hash":"11f63b7"},{"message":"## Step 5. Move the Poles\nIn this step, we will program the animation of the poles. We use the function [`Window.requestAnimationFrame()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/window/requestAnimationFrame). This method tells the browser that you wish to perform an animation and requests that the browser calls a specified function to update an animation before the next repaint.\n\nHere, for every repaint, we are updating the position of the poles by moving them by 2 pixel per frame.","hash":"1e688b5"},{"message":"## Step 6. Clean the Code\nIn this step, let's clean our code for a bit. We will create a new function called `updatePoles()` that takes the moving action. We do this because in the future, we may add new functions to update the bird in the repainting process.","hash":"9c4ddc8"},{"message":"## Step 7. The Restart Logic\nIn this step, we will implement the restart logic. In previous step, if we click on the restart button multiple times, the position of the poles will not be reset. In addition, we will start multiple repainting process if we don't cancel an ongoing process in the restart logic.\n\nWe cancel the previous repainting process by using the `window.cancelAnimationFrame()` API.","hash":"e15ffb1"},{"message":"## Step 8. Make the Poles Looping\nAlright, so far we have implemented the restart button that will move the two poles to the left of the game area. But the poles disappear after moving to the left. What we want is to generate new poles after the old poles disappear.\n\nThus, we will update the position of the poles again to the right of the screen to make it \"looping\".","hash":"ec896f5"},{"message":"## Step 9. Randomize the New Poles' Height\nLastly, let's randomize the new poles' height but keeps the gap consistent in between.  To do so, we use `parseInt(Math.random() * 100)` to generate a random integer between 0 and 100. We use this value to tweak the height of the two poles.","hash":"e21fbb5","recording":"{\"events\":[{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":309,\"y\":375,\"time\":1648670359407},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":295,\"y\":386,\"time\":1648670359415},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":290,\"y\":390,\"time\":1648670359423},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":278,\"y\":399,\"time\":1648670359431},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":269,\"y\":407,\"time\":1648670359439},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":260,\"y\":414,\"time\":1648670359448},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":252,\"y\":420,\"time\":1648670359456},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":245,\"y\":424,\"time\":1648670359464},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":240,\"y\":427,\"time\":1648670359473},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":235,\"y\":431,\"time\":1648670359481},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":234,\"y\":432,\"time\":1648670359489},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":230,\"y\":433,\"time\":1648670359497},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":227,\"y\":435,\"time\":1648670359505},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":225,\"y\":437,\"time\":1648670359513},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":222,\"y\":438,\"time\":1648670359524},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":219,\"y\":440,\"time\":1648670359530},{\"type\":\"mousemove\",\"x\":217,\"y\":442,\"time\":164867035953